# maestroxml

`maestroxml` is a small, standard-library-only Python package for writing MusicXML 4.0 files without working directly with the raw XML structure.

The API is stateful on purpose:

- `Score` keeps track of the current measure and score-wide attributes like time and key.
- `Part` and `voice()` cursors keep track of per-measure note placement.
- The serializer turns those higher-level calls into `score-partwise` MusicXML with measures, attributes, directions, chords, ties, slurs, articulations, repeats, and multi-staff backups.

## Installation

```bash
pip install -e .
```

## Quick Start

```python
from maestroxml import Score

score = Score(title="My Piece", composer="Me")

violin1 = score.add_part("Violin I", instrument="violin")
violin2 = score.add_part("Violin II", instrument="violin")
viola = score.add_part("Viola", instrument="viola")
cello = score.add_part("Cello", instrument="cello")

score.measure(1)
score.time_signature("4/4")
score.key_signature("C major")

violin1.notes("quarter", ["C4", "E4", "G4"])
violin1.notes("eighth", ["A4", "B4"])
violin1.rest("quarter")

score.measure(2)
violin1.note("whole", "C5", tie="start")
violin2.dynamic("mp")
viola.text("dolce")
cello.note("whole", "C3")

chord = ["G3", "B4", "D5"]
for measure_number in range(3, 9):
    score.measure(measure_number)
    cello.note("whole", chord[0])
    viola.note("whole", chord[1])
    violin2.note("whole", chord[2])

score.write("my_piece.musicxml")
```

## API Overview

### `Score`

- `Score(title=None, composer=None, lyricist=None, rights=None)`
- `add_part(name, instrument=None, abbreviation=None, staves=None, clefs=None)`
- `measure(number=None)`
- `time_signature(signature, beat_type=None)`
- `key_signature(signature, mode=None)`
- `to_string()`
- `write(path)`

### `Part` / `VoiceCursor`

- `note(duration, pitch, ...)`
- `notes(duration, pitches, ...)`
- `rest(duration, ...)`
- `chord(duration, pitches, ...)`
- `tempo(bpm, beat_unit="quarter", text=None, placement="above")`
- `dynamic(mark, placement="below")`
- `text(content, placement="above")`
- `clef(clef, staff=1)`
- `repeat_start()`
- `repeat_end(times=None)`
- `ending(number, type)`
- `voice(number, staff=1)`

## Supported Musical Inputs

- Pitches: `C4`, `F#5`, `Bb3`
- Durations: `whole`, `half`, `quarter`, `eighth`, `16th`, `32nd`, `64th`
- Dots: `dots=1`, `dots=2`, ...
- Tuplets: `tuplet=(3, 2)` or `tuplet=(3, 2, "eighth")`
- Key signatures: `"C major"`, `"A minor"`, or `key_signature(2, mode="major")`
- Time signatures: `"4/4"`, `(3, 8)`, or `time_signature(6, 8)`
- Ties/slurs: `tie="start"`, `slur="stop"`, `tie=("stop", "start")`
- Articulations: `["staccato", "accent"]`

## Example: Piano With Two Staves

```python
from maestroxml import Score

score = Score(title="Piano Sketch")
piano = score.add_part("Piano", instrument="piano")

score.measure(1)
score.time_signature("4/4")
score.key_signature("G major")

right_hand = piano.voice(1, staff=1)
left_hand = piano.voice(1, staff=2)

right_hand.notes("quarter", ["G4", "A4", "B4", "D5"])
left_hand.note("half", "G2")
left_hand.note("half", "D3")

print(score.to_string())
```
